sect2.para:
The next section primarily focuses on rapport building in the clinical interviewing and assessment process relating to older adult and minoritized populations. Specifically, older adults (60+ years) enter mental health assessments with a wide range of perceptions about themselves, their environments, the presenting problems, and their providers and healthcare settings. Compared to younger adults, older adults face unique barriers to mental health services, such as lower mental health literacy (i. e., the ability to identify mental health problems and treatments according to the dominant conceptualizations) (Adams et al.,
            2024
         ) and aging stigma (Allen & Sikora, 
            2023
         ). Concerns about stigma are common in older adults in general; however, they may be more pronounced for older adults who are also part of minoritized racial, ethnic, and sexual groups (Inventor et al., 
            2022
         ). In any diverse population, lower mental health literacy and stigma may impact the assessment of depressive disorders in rapport building between the clinician and client, and in symptom reporting in multiple ways, including rapport building and symptom reporting (i. e., whether symptoms are reported and how they are described).

Finally, practicing cultural humility may increase alliance in the clinician-client relationship and further facilitate an open discussion about depressive symptoms and assessment. Broadly, cultural humility is an evolving process including self-examining one’s own cultural awareness, providing interpersonal respect, addressing power imbalances, and an openness to new cultural information (Mosher et al.,
            2017
         ). Research indicates that clinicians who adopt a framework of cultural humility experience stronger therapeutic relationships and are less likely to encounter or contribute to microaggressions when working with diverse clients (Davis et al., 
            2021
         ), highlighting the importance of considering diversity factors in all assessment interactions. Of note, cultural humility involves acknowledging all sources of individual diversity, including (but not limited to): race, ethnicity, age, socioeconomic status, sexual orientation, or values.

Standardized diagnostic and screening tools that have been validated for diverse populations are a critical component of diagnostic interviewing. Although it is beyond the scope of this chapter to provide a comprehensive review of all potential measures, it is critical to examine the evidence of validity with diverse populations prior to selecting measures. Some tools have become well-established with diverse populations. For example, the Patient Health Questionnaire-9 (PHQ-9; Kroenke et al.,
            2010
         ) has shown very good validity in relation to expert clinician interviews and has been used with a wide range of samples, including primary care and other medical patients, individuals from various cultural backgrounds (e. g., diverse populations within the United States, including Latinx and African-American; Nigerian; Thai; Korean; Chinese) (Huang et al.,
            2006
         ), and older adults (Phelan et al., 
            2010
         ).

Despite the value of standardized tools, the individual’s cultural context must be considered while formulating a diagnosis and treatment plan. Cultural context is important to assess, given that clients’ culture impacts all aspects of their help-seeking, including their perceptions of their problems, causes, and potential solutions, and their relationships with providers. It is also important that clinicians recognize that cultural identity is complex and may change over time. For example, a client may strongly identify with both their country of origin and the majority culture in which they live in, or they may identify with neither, with not clear relationship between the two. Instead of assuming a “zero-sum model,” in which the person is viewed as high on one dimension of identity and low on the other, a client may have a low or high sense of identity on each dimension. Immigration status is another important part of cultural identity that may impact distress and stressors. For example, research has shown that the rate of depression in immigrant individuals is lower than that of native-born individuals when they arrive in the United States, but that their risk for psychological distress increases with time spent in the United States (Ikonte et al.,
            2020
         ).

Cultural factors also influence how individuals conceptualize and report their mood symptoms. For example, Hispanic-American adults tend to emphasize somatic symptoms more so than emotional or mood-related symptoms, and are less likely to distinguish between mood and somatic symptoms (Lewis-Fernández et al.,
            2005
         ). A similar pattern has been found with older adults, who may present with more somatic symptoms, including a focus on physical health conditions, agitation, or gastrointestinal symptoms, as well as more anhedonia and fewer depressed or mood-focused symptoms (Hegeman et al., 
            2012
         ). Individuals may also use terms of descriptions not found within the DSM-5 to label their symptoms. For example, Spanish-speaking patients may use a variety of terms to describe their distress or depressive symptoms, such as “desanimado” (discouraged) or “nervios” (Noguera et al., 
            2009
         ). There are also mixed findings on whether Black Americans experience more or less depression as compared to their Non-Hispanic White counterparts, suggesting that the relationship between race and depression is multi-dimensional, and accurate assessment should include assessing for social context, lived experiences (such as systemic racism and discrimination), and individual descriptions of depressive symptoms (Ettman et al., 
            2022
         ). Thus, in assessing and diagnosing depressive disorders, clinicians would use a biopsychosocial conceptualization, validate reported somatic symptoms, and maintain cultural competence.

To introduce a simplified approach for integrating cultural considerations into assessment across disciplines, the DSM-5 Cultural Formulation Interview (CFI) was published in 2013 (Lewis-Fernández et al.,
            2016
         ). The CFI is a semi-structured interview, which was developed based on literature review and field trials in the United States, Canada, India, Kenya, the Netherlands, and Peru. It includes 16 core questions to systematically assess four dimensions: cultural identity of the individual (e. g., reference group, acculturation across host and origin cultures, language), cultural explanations of illness (e. g., idioms and symptom presentation, meaning of illness in relation to cultural norms, perceived explanatory models), cultural factors related to psychosocial environment and levels of functioning (e. g., interpretations of stressors, social networks), and cultural elements of the client-clinician relationship (Lewis-Fernández et al.,
            2016
         ). In addition, the CFI includes 12 supplemental modules that can be used to gather more information; the modules for older adults, immigrants and refugees, and caregivers might be particularly relevant for assessment with diverse older adults and their families. The questions are open-ended, and the authors conceptualize the CFI as a person-centered, ethnographic approach that allows patients to describe their problems, explanations, and experiences in their own words.

Adding the CFI or other questions to assess cultural considerations is a valuable supplement to the standard diagnostic assessment tools, even those that have been validated with diverse populations. Research has provided evidence that the CFI is effective in improving clinical rapport (Lewis-Fernández et al.,
            2020
         ), as well as assisting clinicians with differential diagnosis and treatment planning with diverse populations (Aggarwal, 
            2024
         ). In addition, assessing patients’ multidimensional needs, such as housing, environment, physical, and social needs, also helps the clinician gain a better understanding of the full scope of a client’s presenting problem and how their needs may relate to symptoms of depressive disorders.
